HTML Content for 2024 Spring:
b"<h2>CS360 Midterm Exam - February 29, 2024</h2>\n\nThis exam proved to be challenging to many of you time-wise, which is why I'm sure that\nthe programming questions ended up with such low scores.\n<p>\nHere is the mapping of scores to letter grades.  I don't put plusses and minuses on\nthe grades.  Please see <a href=https://web.eecs.utk.edu/~jplank/General-Teaching/Final_Grades.html>https://web.eecs.utk.edu/~jplank/General-Teaching/Final_Grades.html</a> for how I \nmap exam grades to final grades.\n\n<UL>\n<LI> A+: 78-93.  Special kudos to the three exams >= 89.  Well done!\n<LI> A:  68-78\n<LI> B:  55-68\n<LI> C:  42-55\n<LI> D:  31-42\n<LI> F:   0-31\n</UL>\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Exam, Answers, Grading Rubric</h3>\n\nThe exam was on Canvas, and I used question banks for a few questions.\n<a href=Exam.html>This link is to an example exam.</a>\n<p>\nThe following link has answers and grading information:\n<a href=Answers.html>Answers.html</a>.  It has histograms for each question.\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Histogram and Tukey Plots</h3>\n\nClick on them to blow them up.\n\n<p><center><table border=3><td><a href=Histograms/Total.jpg><img src=Histograms/Total.jpg width=600></a></td></table></center><p>\n<p><center><table border=3><td><a href=Histograms/Tukey.jpg><img src=Histograms/Tukey.jpg width=600></a></td></table></center><p>\n\n"

HTML Content for 2023 Spring:
b"<h2>CS360 Midterm Exam - March 9, 2023</h2>\n\nThis was a pretty standard CS360 midterm.\n<p>\nHere is the mapping of scores to letter grades.  I don't put plusses and minuses on\nthe grades.  Please see <a href=https://web.eecs.utk.edu/~jplank/General-Teaching/Final_Grades.html>https://web.eecs.utk.edu/~jplank/General-Teaching/Final_Grades.html</a> for how I \nmap exam grades to final grades.\n\n<UL>\n<LI> A+: 70-90\n<LI> A:  60-70\n<LI> B:  50-60\n<LI> C:  43-50\n<LI> D:  35-43\n<LI> F:   0-35\n</UL>\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Exam, Answers, Grading Rubric</h3>\n\nThe exam was on Canvas, and I used question banks for one question.\n<a href=example_exam.pdf>This link is to an example exam.</a>\n<p>\nThe following link has answers and grading information:\n<a href=answers.html>answers.html</a>.\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Histogram and Tukey Plots</h3>\n\nClick on them to blow them up.\n\n<p><center><table border=3><td><a href=Histograms/Total.jpg><img src=Histograms/Total.jpg width=600></a></td></table></center><p>\n<p><center><table border=3><td><a href=Histograms/Tukey.jpg><img src=Histograms/Tukey.jpg width=600></a></td></table></center><p>\n\n"

HTML Content for 2022 Spring:
b'<h2>CS360 Midterm Exam - March 8, 2022</h2>\n\nThis ended up being a difficult exam, and time got most of you.  To help, I gave three\nquizzes in Canvas that the students were to do in lab.  They were just like problems\n2-4, and students could replace their scores on problems 2-4 with the results of those\nquizzes.\n\n<p>\nI will express my disappointment in a large number of answers to Questions 5 and 6.\nI expected those questions to have 100% correct, since they are straightforward\nconcepts that are typically on every CS360 midterm that I give.  There was nothing\ntricky -- just show that you know what hard links are and what buffering is.\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Scores to Grades</h3>\n\nHere is the mapping of scores to grades (this is after the quizzes have been\nincorporated):\n\n<pre>\n- A+ 67 - 75\n- A  59 - 67\n- B  48 - 59\n- C  40 - 48\n- D  35 - 40\n- F   0 - 35\n</pre>\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Exam, Answers, Grading Rubric</h3>\n\nThe exam was on Canvas.  The questions, answers and grading are below:\n<a href=answers.html>answers.html</a>.\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Histogram and Tukey Plots</h3>\n\nThe histogram shows the scores after the quizzes have been incorporated.\nThe Tukey plots show the original scores before the quizzes.\n<p><center><table border=3><td><a href=Total.jpg><img src=Total.jpg width=600></a></td></table></center><p>\n\n<p><center><table border=3><td><a href=Tukey.jpg><img src=Tukey.jpg width=600></a></td></table></center><p>\n'

HTML Content for 2021 Spring:
b'<body bgcolor=ffffff>\n\n<h2>CS360 Midterm Exam -- March 9, 2021</h2>\n\n<h3><a href=http://web.eecs.utk.edu/~jplank>James S. Plank</h3></a>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Files</h2>\n\n<UL>\n<LI> <a href=exam.html>The Exam</a>\n<LI> <a href=answers.html>Answers, explanation and grading</a>\n</UL>\n<p>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Comments</h2>\n\nBy and large, I was disappointed by the class performance on this exam.  \nI\'m sorry -- I know my exams are tough, requiring studying, thinking on\nyour feet and attention\nto detail -- but these are skills that I really want every student to acquire\nand strive for.  \n<p>\n\nToo many \nstudents floundered on the assembler question, and on the questions \n(1 and 7) which were pretty much just like the class clicker questions.\nIt also bummed me out at how many students gave <i>O(n<sup>2</sup>)</i>\nsolutions to questions 3 and 4.  We\'ve talked multiple times about question 4 in class,\nand how you cannot treat <b>strcat()</b> like you tread string appending in C++.\nThe use of a proper data structure in question 3 comes from CS140 -- \nif you are on a job interview, and they\nask you to do storage and retrieval, you are not going to get hired\nif you give them a linear search (which results in \n<i>O(n<sup>2</sup>)</i> when you do <i>n</i> of them).\n<p>\nIf you\'re below the B+ range on this exam, I urge you to either study more or\nstudy more effectively for the final exam.  All of my finals from CS360 are\nonline -- one of your studying tools should be to do a sampling of these exams, \ntimed.  That way you\'ll know what the exam feels like, and what the answers should\nfeel like.\n<p>\nHere are scores to grades:\n\n<UL>\n<LI> A:  60 - 80\n<LI> B:  45 - 60\n<LI> C:  35 - 45\n<LI> D:  30 - 35\n<LI> F:   0 - 30\n</ul>\n\n<p>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Total.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Tukey Plots</h2>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Tukey.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<br>\nThis is a Tukey Plot, which has lines to the max and min, yellow box denoting\nthe 1st and 3rd quartiles, hash marks at the median, and dot at the mean.\n<p>\nIn the <a href=answers.html>"answers and grading"</a>, there are histograms of scores for each question.\n'

HTML Content for 2017 Spring 2:
b'<body bgcolor=ffffff>\n\n<h2>CS360 Midterm Exam 2 -- March 21, 2017</h2>\n\n<h3><a href=http://web.eecs.utk.edu/~jplank>James S. Plank</h3></a>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Files</h2>\n\n<UL>\n<LI> <a href=Exam.pdf>The Exam</a>\n<LI> <a href=Answer-Sheet.pdf>The Answer Sheet</a>\n<LI> <a href=answers.html>Answers, explanation and grading</a>\n</UL>\n<p>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Comments</h2>\n\nI thought this was a pretty standard exam.  I did not anticipate that Question 1 would be\nthe hardest.  In fact, I thought I was throwing y\'all a bone with question 1 -- some bit \narithmetic (that didn\'t even make you do operations on bits -- the bit shifts were by multiples\nof four, and the AND and OR operations only involved f\'s and 0\'s) and some very simple pointer\narithmetic.  I was wrong, as the median score on Question 1 was 4 out of 16.\n<p>\nHere is the mapping of scores to grades:\n<UL>\n<LI> A+: 77 - 92 \n<LI> A:  62 - 77\n<LI> B:  52 - 62\n<LI> C:  40 - 52\n<LI> D:  30 - 40\n<LI> F:   0 - 35\n</ul>\n\nHere\'s what I\'m going to do.  On monday in lab, I am going to give you another test.\nIt is going to involve bit arithmetic, type casting and pointer arithmetic.  Like question 1.\nThe exam will\nbe graded on a 16-point scale, and your score on the exam will be added to your score on this\nmidterm.  I want to see EVERYONE in the class get 16 out of 16 on this exam.  This is fundamental\nmaterial -- the kind that interviewers like to ask on interviews.\n\n<p>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Overall.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Tukey Plots</h2>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Tukey.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<br>\nThis is a Tukey Plot, which has lines to the max and min, yellow box denoting\nthe 1st and 3rd quartiles, hash marks at the median, and dot at the mean.\n<p>\nIn the <a href=answers.html>"answers and grading"</a>, there are histograms of scores for each question.\n'

I have come to realize that I test you on what I want you\nto know, and I won\'t compromise on that, even though it is difficult.  I understand\nthat time pressure is what often gets you, and my grading reflects how difficult\nthe time pressure is on you.  Please keep working at this stuff -- it is important\nfor your careers.\n\n<UL>\n<LI> A+: 86 - 109\n<LI> A:  74 - 86\n<LI> B:  60 - 74\n<LI> C:  46 - 60\n<LI> D:  35 - 46\n<LI> F:   0 - 35\n</ul>\n\n<p>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Total.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Tukey Plots</h2>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Tukey.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<br>\nThis is a Tukey Plot, which has lines to the max and min, yellow box denoting\nthe 1st and 3rd quartiles, hash marks at the median, and dot at the mean.\n<p>\nIn the <a href=Answers.html>"answers and grading"</a>, there are histograms of scores for each question.\n\n'

Plank</h3></a>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Files</h2>\n\n<UL>\n<LI> <a href=Exam.pdf>The Exam</a>\n<LI> <a href=Asheet.pdf>Answer Sheets</a>\n<LI> <a href=answers.html>Answers and grading</a>\n</UL>\n<p>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Comments</h2>\n\nThis was a very hard exam.  Once again, I apologize for your stress, but I believe strongly\nthat a true understanding of computer systems requires that you know the bits, bytes and pointers\nand how they interrelate.  This exam tests that, and although it was long and detailed, I believe\nit fairly tested you.  I have given lots of \npartial credit, and have scaled the grades to account for the exam\'s length.  \nIn general, I thought you did well on this challenging\nexam.\n\n<UL>\n<LI> A+: Above 61 - Fantastic job!\n<LI> A: 52 to 51\n<LI> B: 40 to 52\n<LI> C: 30 to 40\n<LI> D: 25 to 30\n<LI> F: Below 25\n</UL> \n<p>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Total.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Tukey Plots</h2>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Tukey.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<br>\nThis is a Tukey Plot, which has lines to the max and min, yellow box denoting\nthe 1st and 3rd quartiles, hash marks at the median, and dot at the mean.\n<p>\nIn the <a href=Answers.html>"answers and grading"</a>, there are histograms of scores for each question.\n\n'

Plank</h3></a>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Files</h2>\n\n<UL>\n<LI> <a href=midterm.html>The exam in HTML</a>\n<LI> <a href=midterm.pdf>The exam in pdf</a>\n<LI> <a href=Q2-Answer-Sheet.pdf>The answer sheet for question 2</a>\n<LI> <a href=q5-scenarios.html>The 12 scenarios for question 5</a>\n<LI> <a href=cheat.html>The cheat sheet</a>\n<LI> <a href=answers.html>Answers and grading</a>\n</UL>\n<p>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Comments</h2>\n\nThis exam was too long.  I\'m sorry about that.  I never intend to write\nexams that take that long, and I don\'t like putting you through that\nstress, which is why I\'ve graded this so quickly. I have scaled the\ngrades so that you could get an A even skipping two of the five problems.\n\n<p>\nThe ranges of grades are below.   I am not breaking up grades into "B+" or "A-".\nInstead, I simply break them up into ABCD, and use those scores to calculate your\nfinal scores.  When I get the final scores, I will break up the B\'s into A-/B+/B,\nand the C\'s into B-/C+/C.\n<p>\nAlso, since this exam was so hard, I will be flexible about its weight on the\nfinal grade.  For example, if you nail the final AND your lab grades are good,\nI will minimize the impact of this exam on your final score.\n<UL>\n<LI> A+: 40 to 60\n<LI> A: 34 to 40\n<LI> B: 28 to 34\n<LI> C: 22 to 28\n<LI> D: 17 to 22\n<LI> F: Below 17\n</UL> \n<p>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Scores.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Tukey Plots</h2>\n<p><center><table border=3 cellpadding=3><td valign=top><IMG src=Tukey.jpg width=600></td></table></center><p>\n<br>\nThis is a Tukey Plot, which has lines to the max and min, yellow box denoting\nthe 1st and 3rd quartiles, hash marks at the median, and dot at the mean.\n<p>\nIn the <a href=answers.html>"answers and grading"</a>, there are histograms of scores for each question.\n\n'

b"<title>CS360 Midterm -- October 18, 2000.</title>\n<body bgcolor=ffffff>\n\n<h2>CS360 Midterm -- October 18, 2000.</h2>\n\n<UL>\n<LI> There are three questions.\n<LI> You have 50 minutes.\n<LI> Do your answers on a separate sheet of paper.\n<LI> Put your name (username is fine) on <i>every sheet</i>.\n</UL>\n<hr>\nMy advice is to do questions 1 and 3 first, and then spend the rest of\nyour time on question 2.  I am giving you plenty of time for this,\nso make your answers good.\n<hr>\n<UL>\n<LI> <a href=q1.html>Question 1</a>, <a href=a1.html>Answer and grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=q2.html>Question 2</a>, <a href=a2.html>Answer and grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=q3.html>Question 3</a>, <a href=a3.html>Answer and grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=cheat_sheet.html>Cheat Sheet</a>\n</UL>\n<hr>\n<h3>Assigning Grades</h3>\n\nOverall, I was pleased with this one.  Most of you showed that you've\ngrasped the material well enough to convince me as such.  Not bad.\n<p>\n\nIn assigning grades, I first like to set the basic competence level. \nHere's my breakdown:\n\n<UL>\n<LI> <b>Question 1:</b> Basic competence: 9 points for the basic stuff\n     plus one mistake.  A good answer should be at least 12 points.\n<LI> <b>Question 2:</b> \n      Basic competence: 11 points\n         (recursive subroutine, opendir, traversal, . and .., \n          proper file name, lstat, checking directories, \n          remove/unlink, recursive call,\n          closedir, error checking).\n      A good answer should be at least 14 points (two right out of the dlist,\n          creating the file name, calling chmod).\n<LI> <b>Question 3:</b>\n      Basic competence: You should get 4 points automatically for setting\n            the setuid bit so you can call it later as your boss.\n      A good answer will be at least 6 points for trying to hide it, and\n        convincing me enough to give you a point for the reasonableness\n        of your hiding it.\n</UL>\n\nThis makes 24 points for a B and 32 for an A.\n<UL>\n<LI> 35 - 38: A+\n<LI> 32 - 35: A\n<LI> 29 - 32: B+\n<LI> 24 - 29: B\n<LI> 22 - 24: C+\n<LI> 16 - 22: C\n<LI> 14 - 16: D\n<LI> Under 14: F\n</UL>\n\n<hr>\n<a href=grade.html>Histograms for each question</a>\n<p>\n<IMG src=q.Total.gif>\n"

That is intentional.  You must pretend that you are a compiler\n     and compile and run the code given.\n</UL>\n<hr>\n<UL>\n<LI> <a href=q1.html>Question 1</a>, <a href=a1.html>Answer and grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=q2.html>Question 2</a>, <a href=a2.html>Answer and grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=q3.html>Question 3</a>, <a href=a3.html>Answer and grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=q4.html>Question 4</a>, <a href=a4.html>Answer and grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=cheat_sheet.html>Cheat Sheet</a>\n</UL>\n<hr>\n<h3>Assigning Grades</h3>\n\nIn assigning grades, I first like to set the basic competence level. \nHere's my breakdown:\n\n<UL>\n<LI> <b>Question 1:</b> Basic competence: 6 points (structure, two \n     tree traversals, checking p->type == 0, printing key.s, details),\n     a good answer should be at least 8 points.\n<LI> <b>Question 2:</b> \n      Basic competence: 11 points (6 points for part 1,\n                        4 points for part 2, one\n                        point for part 3).  A good answer should\n               be at least 14 points.\n<LI> <b>Question 3:</b>\n      Basic competence: 5 points for explaining buffering, \n                        and none for convenience.\n      A good answer is 6 points for a lame genuflect toward convenience.\n<LI> <b>Question 4:</b>\n      Basic competence: 8 points (structure, opendir, return val, traversal,\n                         stat return, print name/recursion, initial call)\n      Good answer: 10 points.\n</UL>\n\nThis makes 30 points for a B, 38 for an A. HTML Content for 1996:
b'<title>CS360 Exam #1. October 25, 1996</title>\n\n<h1>CS360 Exam #1.  October 25, 1996</h1>\n<h2>\n<LI> Jim Plank\n</h2>\n50 points total. Do all questions.\n<hr>\n<h1>Question 1 (10 points)</h1>\n<h3>Part 1 (5 points)</h3>\nExplain why you should use the standard I/O library rather than \nthe file I/O system calls for reading lines of text from a file.\n(Don\'t just give a one word answer -- explain it).\n<h3>Part 2 (5 points)</h3>\nIf you are reading one character at a time from a file, why \nis it better to use <b>getchar()</b> or <b>fgetc()</b> rather than\n<b>fread()</b>?\n\n<hr>\n<h1>Question 2 (12 points)</h1>\nConvert the following C code into (unoptimized) assembler.  \nUse only registers <b>r0</b> and <b>r1</b> (plus of course the\nstack and frame pointers).\n<pre>\nmain(int argc, char **argv)\n{\n  int i, j;\n\n  j = 0;\n  while(argc > 0) {\n    i = j + 5;\n    j = main(b(j), i-1);\n  }\n}\n</pre>\n\n\n<hr>\n<h1>Question 3 (14 points)</h1>\n<h3>Part 1 (12 points)</h3>\nWrite the program <b>parent</b> that prints the name of the\nparent directory of the current directory.  In other words, \nthe following should be the output of <b>parent</b>:\nYou may <i>not</i> use <b>system()</b>, <b>getcwd()</b> or\n<b>getenv()</b>.\n<pre>\nUNIX> cd /mahogany/homes/plank\nUNIX> pwd\n/mahogany/homes/plank\nUNIX> parent\nplank\nUNIX> cd papers\nUNIX> pwd\n/mahogany/homes/plank/papers\nUNIX> parent\npapers\nUNIX>\n</pre>\nSee the last page of this test for prototypes of C library calls\nand system calls that may be helpful.\n<h3>Part 2 (2 points)</h3>\nWhat will be the output of:\n<pre>\nUNIX> cd /\nUNIX> parent\n</pre>\n\n\n<hr>\n<h1>Question 4 (14 points)</h1>\n\nThis question concerns the program <b>printword</b>.  This \nprogram takes a file on standard input, and sorts the words.  For\neach word, it prints out the line numbers (sorted) that contain\nthe word.\nIt skips lines whose first word starts with the \'#\' character.\nIt should not print out a line number twice for the same word.\n\n<p>Thus, for the following file:\n<pre>\nUNIX> cat geh\n# Beginning\nI am Sam\nI am Sam\nSam I am\n   That Sam I am   That Sam I am    I do not like that Sam I am\n # end\nUNIX> \n</pre>\nThe output of the program should be the following:\n<pre>\nUNIX> wordline < geh\nI: 2, 3, 4, 5\nSam: 2, 3, 4, 5\nThat: 5\nam: 2, 3, 4, 5\ndo: 5\nlike: 5\nnot: 5\nthat: 5\nUNIX>\n</pre>\nNow, behold the following code for <b>printword</b>:\n<pre>\n#include < stdio.h >\n#include "fields.h"\n#include "rb.h"\n\nmain()\n{\n  IS is;\n  Rb_node t, tmp;\n  char *s;\n  int i, fnd;\n\n  t = make_rb();\n  is = new_inputstruct(NULL);\n\n  while(get_line(is) > 0) {\n    if (is->text1[0] != \'#\') {\n      for (i = 0; i < is->NF; i++) {\n        tmp = rb_find_key_n(t, is->fields[i], &fnd);\n        if (!fnd || is->line != (int) (tmp->v.val)) {\n          rb_insert(t, is->fields[i], (char *) (is->line));\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  s = NULL;\n  rb_traverse(tmp, t) {\n    if (strcmp(s, tmp->k.key) != 0) {\n      if (s != NULL) printf("\\n");\n      printf("%s: %d", tmp->k.key, (int) (tmp->v.val));\n    } else {\n      printf(", %d", (int) (tmp->v.val));\n    }\n    s = tmp->k.key;\n  }\n  printf("\\n");\n}\n</pre>\nThere are five bugs in this program.  By ``bug\'\', I mean that they\nwill cause incorrect output (or core dumpage), not inefficiency.\nFour of them are simple\nand can be fixed within the line that they occur.  The fifth is\na disign flaw in the program.  For each of these bugs:\n<UL>\n<LI> Identify the bug and state what behavior the bug will\n     cause.\n<LI> State how the fix the bug.  For the four simple bugs, fix them.\n     For the fifth, state how you have to redesign the program so that\n     it is no longer a bug.  Make sure that this new design is efficient, \n     at least as far as CPU time is concerned (don\'t worry about memory\n     usage).\n</UL>\nNote -- <b>none of the bugs are syntax/compiler errors.</b>  This\ncode will compile just fine.  They are all functional errors.\n\n<p>Again, prototypes of relevant C functions and structs are at the\nend of the test.\n'

HTML Content for 1996:
b'<title>Answers: CS360 Exam #1. October 25, 1996</title>\n\n<h1>Answers: CS360 Exam #1.  October 25, 1996</h1>\n<h2>\n<LI> Jim Plank\n</h2>\n<hr>\n<h1>General Comments</h1>\nThe test went about as expected.  It was challenging, but not overwhelming.\nI apologize for the confusion with question 3, but most of you seemed to\nunderstand the question ok.  The way I anticipated the test going was:\n<UL>\n<LI> Question 1: A giveaway -- straight from the lecture notes.\n<LI> Question 2: Easier than your lab -- should take a few minutes, but\n     if you did lab 7, you should have done fine.\n<LI> Question 3: Requires thought and coding.  Not surprisingly, the\n     scores showed a lot of variance.\n<LI> Question 4: Subtle code reading -- a very difficult question to\n     do on a timed, test, but the grading was lenient -- you only needed\n     to find 3.5 bugs out of 5 to get a perfect score.\n</UL>\n\nTo see the score distribution see the \nhistogram of final grades and Tukey plots below.\n\n<p>As far translating numbers into grades, I\'d say:\n<UL>\n<LI>Over 45: A+\n<LI>35 -- 45: A\n<LI>30 -- 34: B to B+\n<LI>25 -- 29: C+\n<LI>20 -- 24: C\n<LI>15 -- 19: D\n<LI>10 -- 14: F\n</UL>\nThe distinction between B and A is blurry.  Below 30 means you should\nbe striving to improve (and have good lab scores).\n\n<hr>\n<h2>Histogram of exam scores</h2>\n<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="q.Total.gif">\n\n<h2>Tukey plots of exam scores</h2>\n<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="Tukey.gif">\n\n<p>(the \nline goes from min to max, the box from 1st quartile to 3rd quartile, \ndot at the mean and hash lines at the median).\n<hr>\n<h1>Question 1 (10 points)</h1>\n<i>\n<h3>Part 1 (5 points)</h3>\nExplain why you should use the standard I/O library rather than \nthe file I/O system calls for reading lines of text from a file.\n(Don\'t just give a one word answer -- explain it).\n<h3>Part 2 (5 points)</h3>\nIf you are reading one character at a time from a file, why \nis it better to use <b>getchar()</b> or <b>fgetc()</b> rather than\n<b>fread()</b>?\n</i>\n<h2>Answer</h2>\n<h3>Part 1 (5 points)</h3>\nThe standard I/O library performs buffering.  That is, when you read\na small number of bytes from a file using the standard I/O library\nusing a procedure like <b>fgets()</b>,\nit reads a large chunk of bytes into a buffer with one <b>read()</b>\nsystem call.  Subsequent <b>fgets()</b> calls then read from the \nbuffer until the buffer is empty, at which point it is filled anew\nwith another <b>read()</b> call.  Since system calls are expensive,\nthis strategy takes much less time than performing a <b>read()</b>\ncall for each line of text.\n\n<h3>Part 2 (5 points)</h3>\n<b>Getchar()</b> and <b>fgetc()</b> are optimized to perform buffered\nI/O of single bytes using the standard I/O library.  Think of what\n<b>getchar()</b> needs to do:\n<OL>\n<LI>Check to see if the buffer is empty.\n<LI>If empty, fill it with a <b>read</b> call.\n<LI>Increment the pointer to the head of the buffer, and return the byte\n    in the old head to the user.\n</OL>\nContrast that with what <b>fread()</b> must do:\n<OL>\n<LI>Calculate the size of the request.\n<LI>Check to see if there are enough characters left in the buffer to\n    satisfy the request.\n<LI>If so, copy the bytes using from the buffer to the given pointer.\n<LI>If not, copy as many bytes as you can, refill the buffer, and try \n    again.\n</OL>\nWhile you don\'t have to do some of these steps when calling <b>fread()</b>\nfor single bytes, there is still more processing that must be done.  In\nfact, the pushing of 4 arguments onto the stack rather than zero (for\n<b>getchar()</b>) and one (for <b>fgetc()</b>) will mkae <b>fread()</b>\nperform poorly when compared to the others for the same tasks.\n\n<h2>Grading</h2>\nGrading of this question was straightforward.  If you said ``<b>getchar()</b>\nand <b>fgetc()</b> are optimized for reading one character while <b>fread()</b>\nis not\'\', you received 4 points on part 2.  You had to give some more detail\nto get the final point.\n\n<h2>Histogram of scores</h2>\n<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="q.1.gif">\n\n<hr>\n<h1>Question 2 (12 points)</h1>\n<i>\nConvert the following C code into (unoptimized) assembler.  \nUse only registers <b>r0</b> and <b>r1</b> (plus of course the\nstack and frame pointers).\n<pre>\nmain(int argc, char **argv)\n{\n  int i, j;\n\n  j = 0;\n  while(argc > 0) {\n    i = j + 5;\n    j = main(b(j), i-1);\n  }\n}\n</pre>\n</i>\n<h2>Answer</h2>\nNote that I have <b>i</b> at <b>[fp-4]</b> and <b>j</b> at <b>[fp]</b>.\nSome of you had the opposite, but that\'s fine.\n<pre>\nmain:\n\tpush #8            / Allocate i and j, i is at [fp-4], j is at [fp]\n\n        st %g0 -> [fp]     / Set j to zero\nl1:\n        ld [fp+12] -> %r0  / Test for argc > 0\n        cmp %r0, %g0\n        ble l2         \n        \n        ld [fp] -> %r0       / Do i = j + 5.  Note you have to put 5 into\n        mv #5 -> %r1         / a register before doing the addition\n        add %r0, %r1 -> %r0\n        st %r0 -> [fp-4]\n\n        ld [fp-4] -> %r0     / Push i-1 onto the stack\n        add %r0, %gm1 -> %r0\n        st %r0 -> [sp]--\n\n        ld [fp] -> %r0       / Call b(j) and put the return value\n        st %r0 -> [sp]--     / (which is in r0) on the stack\n        jsr b\n        pop #4\n        st %r0 -> [sp]--\n \n        jsr main             / Call main and store the return value in j\n        pop #8\n        st %r0 -> [fp]\n\n        b l1                 / Go back to the top of the while statement\nl2:\n        ret\n</pre>\n<h2>Grading</h2>\nGrading was broken up into the following parts:\n<UL>\n<LI> Allocating space for i and j: 1 point\n<LI> Setting j to zero: 1 point\n<LI> Doing the while statement correctly: 2 points\n<LI> Doing <b>i = j + 5</b> correctly: 2 points\n<LI> Pushing i-1 on the stack: 1 point\n<LI> Calling <b>b</b> correctly, including popping <b>j</b> off the\n     stack at the end: 1 points\n<LI> Pushing the return value of <b>b</b> on the stack: 1 point\n<LI> Calling <b>main</b> correctly, including popping the arguments\n     off the stack: 1 point\n<LI> Setting <b>j</b> to the return value of <b>main</b>: 1 point\n<LI> Calling <b>ret</b> at the end: 1 point\n</UL>\n\nIf you did something that affected all parts, you received the following\ndeductions (and these were not included in the above assessment):\n<UL>\n<LI> Accessing <b>i</b> and <b>j</b> from <b>sp</b> instead of from \n     <b>fp</b>:      -2\n<LI> Using <b>add</b> instead of <b>push/pop</b>:         -1\n<LI> Assuming that the return values are in <b>r1</b> instead of\n     <b>r0</b>: -1\n<LI> Pushed arguments to <b>main</b> in wrong order: -2\n</UL>\nAt the end, half points were rounded up.\n\n\n<h2>Histogram of scores</h2>\n<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="q.2.gif">\n\n<hr>\n<h1>Question 3 (14 points)</h1>\nSo, as Kim pointed out in class, my definition of <b>parent</b> \nleft something to be desired.  What I meant to say was that\n<b>parent</b> prints out the name of the current directory as\nit appears in the parent directory.   That is what my examples\nshow.  However, if you printed out the name of the parent directory,\nyou received full credit.\n\n<i>\n<h3>Part 1 (12 points)</h3>\nWrite the program <b>parent</b> that prints the name of the\nparent directory of the current directory.  In other words, \nthe following should be the output of <b>parent</b>:\nYou may <i>not</i> use <b>system()</b>, <b>getcwd()</b> or\n<b>getenv()</b>.\n<pre>\nUNIX> cd /mahogany/homes/plank\nUNIX> pwd\n/mahogany/homes/plank\nUNIX> parent\nplank\nUNIX> cd papers\nUNIX> pwd\n/mahogany/homes/plank/papers\nUNIX> parent\npapers\nUNIX>\n</pre>\nSee the last page of this test for prototypes of C library calls\nand system calls that may be helpful.\n<h3>Part 2 (2 points)</h3>\nWhat will be the output of:\n<pre>\nUNIX> cd /\nUNIX> parent\n</pre>\n</i>\n<h2>Answer</h2>\n<h3>Part 1 (12 points)</h3>\nWhat you needed to do was find out the inode number of the current\ndirectory.  You do that by calling <b>stat()</b> and using the <b>st_ino</b>\nfield.  Then, you traverse the <b>..</b> directory and look for an entry\nwhose inode (kept in the <b>d_fileno</b> field) number matches.  When\nyou find that match, print out the name of that directory entry.\nThe code is as follows:\n<pre>\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <dirent.h>\n#include <sys/stat.h>\n  \nmain()\n{\n  struct stat buf;\n  int i;\n  int inode;\n  DIR *d;\n  struct dirent *de;\n\n  if (stat(".", &buf) < 0) { perror("stat"); exit(1); }\n\n  inode = buf.st_ino;\n\n  d = opendir("..");\n  if (d == NULL) { perror("opendir"); exit(1); }\n  for (de = readdir(d); de != NULL; de = readdir(d)) {\n    if (de->d_fileno == inode) {\n      printf("%s\\n", de->d_name);\n      exit(0);\n    }\n  }\n  printf("If my program gets here, life is unhappy....\\n");\n}\n</pre>\n<h3>Part 2 (2 points)</h3>\nSince <b>..</b> equals <b>.</b>, it will print out either <b>..</b> or\n<b>.</b>, depending on which is gets to first (and on our systems, it\nwill get to <b>..</b> first).  \n\n<h2>Grading</h2>\n\nThere are really two parts to this program: performing <b>stat</b> on\n<b>.</b> (or <b>..</b> if you tried to print out the parent directory)\nand saving the inode number, and traversing <b>..</b> (or <b>../..</b>\nif you tried to print out the parent directory) and trying to match the\ninodes.  If you did a reasonable approximation of those two parts, then\nyou started off with 12 points, and were deducted for things that were\nwrong.\n\n<p>If you did some random <b>stat</b> and directory traversal, then\nyou started off with 8 points, and were deducted for things that were\negregiously wrong.  Also, if you used <b>realpath</b> instead of\n<b>stat</b>/<b>opendir</b> you started here.\n\n<p>If you wrote little that made sense you got a few points, the number\nof which depended on how much sense you made.\n\n<p>For part 2, you had to write something reasonable to get points.\n\n<h2>Histogram of scores</h2>\n<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="q.3.gif">\n\n<hr>\n<h1>Question 4 (14 points)</h1>\n<i>\n\nThis question concerns the program <b>printword</b>.  This \nprogram takes a file on standard input, and sorts the words.  For\neach word, it prints out the line numbers (sorted) that contain\nthe word.\nIt skips lines whose first word starts with the \'#\' character.\nIt should not print out a line number twice for the same word.\n\n<p>Thus, for the following file:\n<pre>\nUNIX> cat geh\n# Beginning\nI am Sam\nI am Sam\nSam I am\n   That Sam I am   That Sam I am    I do not like that Sam I am\n # end\nUNIX> \n</pre>\nThe output of the program should be the following:\n<pre>\nUNIX> wordline < geh\nI: 2, 3, 4, 5\nSam: 2, 3, 4, 5\nThat: 5\nam: 2, 3, 4, 5\ndo: 5\nlike: 5\nnot: 5\nthat: 5\nUNIX>\n</pre>\nNow, behold the following code for <b>printword</b>:\n<pre>\n#include < stdio.h >\n#include "fields.h"\n#include "rb.h"\n\nmain()\n{\n  IS is;\n  Rb_node t, tmp;\n  char *s;\n  int i, fnd;\n\n  t = make_rb();\n  is = new_inputstruct(NULL);\n\n  while(get_line(is) > 0) {\n    if (is->text1[0] != \'#\') {\n      for (i = 0; i < is->NF; i++) {\n        tmp = rb_find_key_n(t, is->fields[i], &fnd);\n        if (!fnd || is->line != (int) (tmp->v.val)) {\n          rb_insert(t, is->fields[i], (char *) (is->line));\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  s = NULL;\n  rb_traverse(tmp, t) {\n    if (strcmp(s, tmp->k.key) != 0) {\n      if (s != NULL) printf("\\n");\n      printf("%s: %d", tmp->k.key, (int) (tmp->v.val));\n    } else {\n      printf(", %d", (int) (tmp->v.val));\n    }\n    s = tmp->k.key;\n  }\n  printf("\\n");\n}\n</pre>\nThere are five bugs in this program.  By ``bug\'\', I mean that they\nwill cause incorrect output (or core dumpage), not inefficiency.\nFour of them are simple\nand can be fixed within the line that they occur.  The fifth is\na disign flaw in the program.  For each of these bugs:\n<UL>\n<LI> Identify the bug and state what behavior the bug will\n     cause.\n<LI> State how the fix the bug.  For the four simple bugs, fix them.\n     For the fifth, state how you have to redesign the program so that\n     it is no longer a bug.  Make sure that this new design is efficient, \n     at least as far as CPU time is concerned (don\'t worry about memory\n     usage).\n</UL>\nNote -- <b>none of the bugs are syntax/compiler errors.</b>  This\ncode will compile just fine.  They are all functional errors.\n\n<p>Again, prototypes of relevant C functions and structs are at the\nend of the test.\n</i>\n\n<h2>Answer</h2>\nThe bugs:\n<OL> \n<LI> In the statement:\n<pre>\n  while(get_line(is) > 0) {\n</pre>\nThe > should be changed to >=.  Otherwise, the program will exit the\nfirst time it sees a blank line.\n<LI>The statement:\n<pre>\n  if (is->text1[0] != \'#\') {\n</pre>\nis wrong, because it only tests the first character of each line.  Lines\nthat start with \'#\' but not at the first character will not be omitted.\nIt should be:\n<pre>\n  if (is->NF > 0 && is->fields[0][0] != \'#\') {\n</pre>\n<LI>The <b>rb_insert</b> statement should be called as follows:\n<pre>\n     rb_insert(t, strdup(is->fields[i]), (char *) (is->line));\n</pre>\nSince each <b>get_line()</b> does not implicitly call  <b>malloc()</b>, \nthe string inserted into the rb-tree will be overwritten each time\n<b>get_line()</b> is called.\n<LI>The following line:\n<pre>\n    if (strcmp(s, tmp->k.key) != 0) {\n</pre>\nis going to cause a segmentation violation when it is first called, since\n<b>s</b> is NULL.  There are several ways around this.  A simple one\nis to change the line to:\n<pre>\n    if (s == NULL || strcmp(s, tmp->k.key) != 0) {\n</pre>\n<LI>\nThe design flaw is that words are inserted into the rb-tree if the combination\nof [word,line] is not in the tree.  However, the rb-tree library does not\nguarantee that if you insert a word twice, you can make any assumptions about\nwhere the first and second word are.  Thus, the line numbers will not be\nsorted, and there may be line numbers multiply inserted.  To fix this,\nyou must either have a secondary rb-tree for each word which is the line\nnumber, or you can use "rb_insertg", and have the key field be a pointer\nto a struct with both the word and line numbers.  In both cases,\nyou\'ll have to alter the printing loop too.\n</OL>\n\n<h2>Grading</h2>\nEach bug was worth 4 points: one for identifying the bug, one for describing\nwhat it does, one for fixing it, and an extra one if you got all three \npoints for a bug.  At the end, you get the minimum of\nyour score and 14.\n\n<h2>Histogram of scores</h2>\n<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="q.4.gif">\n\n\n'

b'<TITLE>CS360 Exam #1 Struct and Procedure definitions</title>\n\n<h2>CS360 Exam #1 Struct and Procedure definitions</h2>\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Stat</h3>\n\n<pre>\n   #include <sys/types.h>\n   #include <sys/stat.h>\n\n   int stat(char *path, struct stat buf)\n\n   struct stat {\n        ino_t     st_ino;        /* the file serial number */\n        mode_t    st_mode;       /* file mode */\n        nlink_t   st_nlink;      /* number of hard links to the file */\n        uid_t     st_uid;        /* user ID of owner */\n        gid_t     st_gid;        /* group ID of owner */\n        off_t     st_size;       /* total size of file, in bytes */\n        time_t    st_atime;      /* file last access time */\n        time_t    st_mtime;      /* file last modify time */\n        time_t    st_ctime;      /* file last status change time */\n   };\n</pre>\n\n<hr>\n<h3>Opendir, etc</h3>\n<pre>\n   DIR *opendir(char *dirname)\n   struct dirent *readdir(DIR *dirp)\n   int closedir(DIR *dirp) \n\n   struct  dirent {\n           off_t           d_off;          /* offset of next disk dir entry */\n           unsigned long   d_fileno;       /* file (inode) number of entry */\n           unsigned short  d_reclen;       /* length of this record */\n           unsigned short  d_namlen;       /* length of string in d_name */\n           char            d_name[255+1];  /* name (up to MAXNAMLEN + 1) */\n   };\n</pre>\n<hr>\n<h3>Rb-trees</h3>\n<pre>\n  Rb_node make_rb();   /* Creates a new rb-tree */\n  Rb_node rb_insert(Rb_node tree, char *key, char *val);\n  Rb_node rb_find_key_n(Rb_node root, char *key, int *found);\n\n  #define rb_first(n) (n->c.list.flink)\n  #define rb_next(n) (n->c.list.flink)\n  #define rb_nil(t) (t)\n\n  #define rb_traverse(ptr, lst) \\\n    for(ptr = rb_first(lst); ptr != rb_nil(lst); ptr = rb_next(ptr))\n</pre>\n<hr>\n<h3>Fields</h3>\n<pre>\n  #define MAXLEN 1001\n  #define MAXFIELDS 1000\n  \n  typedef struct inputstruct {\n    char *name;               /* File name */\n    FILE *f;                  /* File descriptor */\n    int line;                 /* Line number */\n    char text1[MAXLEN];       /* The line */\n    char text2[MAXLEN];       /* Working -- contains fields */\n    int NF;                   /* Number of fields */\n    char *fields[MAXFIELDS];  /* Pointers to fields */\n    int file;                 /* 1 for file, 0 for popen */\n  } *IS;\n  \n  extern IS new_inputstruct(/* FILENAME -- NULL for stdin */);\n  extern int get_line(/* IS */); /* returns NF, or -1 on EOF.  Does not\n                                    close the file */\n</pre>\n'

HTML Content for 1999:
b"<title>CS360 Final -- December 11, 1999.</title>\n<body bgcolor=ffffff>\n\n<h2>CS360 Final -- December 11, 1999.</h2>\n\n<UL>\n<LI> There are four questions.\n<LI> You have 2 hours.\n<LI> Each question should take roughly the same amount of time.\n<LI> Do your answers on a separate sheet of paper.\n<LI> Question 2 and part of question 4 have answer sheets for you\n     to fill in.\n</UL>\n<hr>\n<UL>\n<LI> <a href=q1.html>Question 1</a>, <a href=a1.html>Answers and Grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=q2.html>Question 2</a>, <a href=a2.html>Answers and Grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=q3.html>Question 3</a>, <a href=a3.html>Answers and Grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=q4.html>Question 4</a>, <a href=a4.html>Answers and Grading</a><br>\n<LI> <a href=cheat_sheet.html>Cheat Sheet</a>\n</UL>\n\n<hr>\n<h2>General Comments</h2>\n\nSo this was a difficult exam.  Questions 1 and 2 were hard, and question \nthree took some thought.  Question 4 was straightforward.  This exam stressed\nthe ability to write understandable code under time pressure.  I know that\nsome of you have more trouble with that and are better at writing code\nwhen you have the chance to test it and use a debugger, but I believe that\none of the best ways to communicate that you are thinking along the \nright lines is to be able to spew out code such as required in this exam.\n<p>\nWhile questions 1 and 2 caused the most trouble, they were basically\nmaterial from labs 6 and 7.  I was especially surprised that all the \npointer gyrations of question 1 were handled for the most part poorly.\nYou did have to do roughly the same thing in lab 6.  When I see the \nquantity of gibberish that I saw for answers to questions 1 and 2, it makes\nme wonder if you are actually doing the labs, or if you are getting your\nlab answers by other means.  This is one of the reasons that I write\ncoding exams.\n<p>\n\n<h2>Grading</h2>\n\nAs usual, I like to set levels for A's and B's based on the grading of\neach question:\n<UL>\n<LI><b>Question 1</b>: I'd call a 7 the minimal competent grade, getting\n1 point for pointer manipulation, 1 point for the checksum, two points\nfor checking the size, one point for decrementing the size.\nand 2 points for hooking it into the list.  All of you should know\nhow to make a program dump core, so should call this a 9 instead of a 7.\nFor an A, you should have at least an 11.\n<LI><b>Question 2</b>: For the B level, I'd say 8 points: Calling\npipe once, fork() twice, dup2, execlp, exit, fdopen, and \nhaving the child code be the same in both children.  For an A, \nI'd add getting most of the closes right and calling pipe the second time: \n11 points.\n<LI><b>Question 3</b>: For the B level, 3 points for part 1, 2 for part 2,\n3 for part 3 and 2 for part 4: 10 points.  For an A you should have at least\na 13.\n<LI><b>Question 4</b>: For a B, I'd say 7 points for part 1\n(2.5 points for the code in main, 6.5 points for service-thread (missing\nfree, *t->nchars, and another random half point), and perhaps a 2 point\ndeduction for your mutex.).  Everyone should get two points for part 2.\nThat's 9 points.  For an A, you should get everything but two points and\non part 1 (forgetting to free(t), and a random error),\nand again 2 points on part 2.  That's a 12.\n</UL>\nOk, so that's 34 points for a B, and 47 for an A.  I'll subtract 4 points\ndue to you being stressed out due to time pressure, and that gives the\nfollowing grade ranges:\n\n<UL>\n<LI> Above 50: A+ -- congratulate yourself on acing a difficult exam!\n<LI> 43 to 50: A\n<LI> 39 to 43: B+\n<LI> 30 to 39: B\n<LI> 25 to 30: C\n<LI> 20 to 25: D\n<LI> Below 20: F\n</UL>\n\n<hr>\n<h2><a href=grade.html>Histograms for each question</a></h2>\n\n<img src=q.Total.gif>\n"

HTML Content for 1996:
b'<title>Syntax of system and library calls</title>\n<h1>Syntax of system and library calls</h1>\n\n<hr>\n<h1>fork(), pipe(), dup(), execlp(), wait()</h1>\n<pre>\nint fork()\n\nint pipe(fd)\nint fd[2];\n\nint dup2(fd1, fd2)\n\nint execlp(file, arg0 [ , arg1,...  , argn ] (char *)0)\nchar *file, *arg0, *arg1, ..., *argn;\n\nint wait(statusp)\nint *statusp;\n</pre>\n\n<hr>\n<h1>setjmp()/longjmp()</h1>\n\n<pre>\n#include < setjmp.h >\n\nint setjmp(env)\njmp_buf env;\n\nvoid longjmp(env, val)\njmp_buf env;\nint val;\n</pre>\n\n<hr>\n<h1>malloc()/free()</h1>\n<pre>\nchar *malloc(size)\nint size;\n\nint free(ptr)\nchar *ptr;\n</pre>\n\n\n<hr>\n<h1>select() and friends</h1>\n<pre>\n#include < sys/types.h >\n#include < sys/time.h >\n\nint select (width, readfds, writefds, exceptfds, timeout)\nint width;\nfd_set *readfds, *writefds, *exceptfds;\nstruct timeval *timeout;\n\nFD_SET (fd, &fdset)\nFD_CLR (fd, &fdset)\nFD_ISSET (fd, &fdset)\nFD_ZERO (&fdset)\nint fd;\nfd_set fdset;\n</pre>\n'
